name: Justin Seiber
blurb: The NPSL Cascade Division’s Co-Offensive Back of the Year completed 66.4 percent of his passes for 3,297 yards with 36 touchdowns and seven interceptions.

name: Jonny Barrett
blurb: Set a school record for receiving yards in a season with 1,004 on 66 catches with 15 touchdowns. Named to the All-Kingco 4A first-team on offense.

name: Talan Alfrey
blurb: The BYU commit averaged 120 receiving yards per game, finishing with 1,081  on 68 catches with 12 touchdowns. Two-way player named NPSL Olympic Division Defensive Player of the Year.

name: Isaiah Ifanse
blurb: Elusive player finished with 2,091 rushing yards on 207 carries to help Wolverines reach the Class 3A state semifinals. He was named Kingco 3A Offensive MVP.

name: Delvon McNeely
blurb: Key cog for the Highlanders with 1,514 rushing yards with 23 touchdowns. Named the NPSL Cascade Division’s Co-Offensive Back of the Year.

name: Anthony Stell
blurb: amed to the Metro League Mountain Division’s first-team in helping Rainier Beach advance to its first state title game.

name: Matthew Cindric
blurb: A California commit, Cindric was named the Kingco 4A Lineman of the Year. The Spartans advanced to the state tournament quarterfinals.

name: Cade Beresford
blurb: The Washington State commit was named to the All-Kingco 4A  first team. The Falcons were undefeated in league play and advanced to the state tournament finals.

name: Nathaniel Kalepo
blurb: Made a name for himself in just the second season starting on the offensive line, helping the Vikings to the state title game.

name: Jackson Reed
blurb: Named to the All-Metro League Mountain Division’s first-team and was a key reason the top-ranked Crusaders reached the state quarterfinals.

name: Griffin Korican
blurb: The Colorado School of Mines commit was named Offensive Lineman of the Year for the Metro League’s Mountain Division.

name: Brock Widman
blurb: Widmann went 69 for 71 on PATs. He also made all four of the field goals he attempted, the longest being 32 yards.

name: Tiano Malietufa
blurb: The NPSL Olympic Division’s Offensive MVP totaled 2,373 total yards as the starting quarterback. On defense, he had 70 total tackles.

name: Jake Baillie
blurb: Captain of one of the best defenses in the state, the “Dark Side,” Baillie had 12 sacks and was named Kingco 4A MVP for defense.

name: Matt Sevao
blurb: Set a program record with 17 sacks and 118 total tackles  to help the Vikings clinch a seventh-straight Wesco 4A league title. Named all-league first team on defense.

name: Davion Dixon
blurb: Named the Metro League Mountain Division’s Defensive Lineman of the Year. O’Dea advanced to the Class 3A state finals.

name: Justus Legg
blurb: The four-star recruit helped the Ravens open the 2017 season with three straight shutouts. Named to the NPSL’s Olympic Division’s first-team on defense.

name: Ricky Baker
blurb: The Wesco 4A first-team pick helped the Bearcats win the first state tournament game in school history. Had 93 solo tackles – 142 total – with seven sacks and one interception.

name: Sav'ell Smalls
blurb: Already garnering interest from schools such as Notre Dame and Alabama, he helped Bulldogs advance to first Class 3A state semifinal since 1977. Metro League Co-Defensive MVP has 90 tackles with nine sacks.

name: Dominic Lawrence
blurb: Helped the Warriors go undefeated in Wesco 3A/2A South Division play and advance to the state tournament for first time since 2011. Named all-league first team on defense.

name: Ryan Taylor
blurb: Taylor, who was named All-Metro League Mountain Division first-team, finished with 91 tackles and three sacks.

name: Malik Putney
blurb: The team captain, named the Metro League’s Mountain Division’s Co-Defensive MVP, had five interceptions. One was a school-record 99-yard touchdown return to advance the Crusaders to the Class 3A state quarterfinals.

name: Kyler Gordon
blurb: The four-star recruit helped the Wildcats win back-to-back Cascade Conference titles and advance to the Class 2A state semifinals the year after winning state. Had five interceptions and a combined 10 touchdowns on offense and special teams.

name: Nash Fouch
blurb: The first-team all-Kingco 4A pick is part of the “Dark Side” defense that is tops in the state. Was named to the Star Times team as a receiver last year and is committed to Montana.

name: Jaden Robinson
blurb: Named the NPSL’s Olympic Division’s Defense Back of the Year after totaling six interceptions for the Ravens. Also used on special teams.

name: Lance D'Alessio
blurb: The Kingco 3A first-team pick had 48 punts this season for 1,852 total yards, the longest being 54-yards. Also averaged 54.2 yards on kickoffs and hit 28 of his 36 PAT attempts.

name: Mark Gunderson
blurb: In his sixth season, the NPSL Olympic Division Coach of the Year helped the Hornets win their first division title in 21 seasons. Finished  8-3 with a state preliminary round appearance.
